observations.recommendation:
We recommended and management agreed to:
craft an internal policy on the provision of impairment of receivables that are long overdue, in accordance with IPSAS 29;
conduct a collaborative effort with the CAO and CCDO to evaluate the status of NGO/ PO beneficiaries and identify those that would impair the receivable account balance from NGOs and POs;
instruct the City Accountant to prepare the necessary adjusting journal entry to recognize the determined impairment in accordance with IPSAS 29; and
comply all the conditions and requirements of COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016 and request for the write-off of the specified dormant receivables to the Commission on Audit.

Henceforth, we recommended and the management agreed to:
require the immediate reporting of defective odometers to the CGSO for appropriate action;
reassess their review process prior to granting fuel requests, taking into consideration the actual tank capacity of each vehicle.  Management may consider attaching the recent trip ticket to determine the existing fuel in tank prior to request for refueling;
stop the practice of granting of fuel more than the maximum fuel tank capacity;
require detailed drivers to accomplish the trip tickets properly and completely, indicating all of the required information;
consider entering into an agreement when utilizing privately-owned vehicles to accelerate the COVID-19 mitigation operations;
revisit their operational controls in fuel consumption and strengthen their review process of documents supporting requests for fuel withdrawal; and
consider creating a database of all vehicles used for any program or project implementation to better establish the veracity of fuel requests and charges against government funds.

We recommended and the management agreed that the City Treasurer:
reassess the overall internal control system in the CTO, identify critical points of breakdown and make necessary correcting measures to prevent fraudulent actions;
strengthen the security measures to maintain the veracity of database by requesting the Service Provider of RPTBS to make necessary changes in the program, such that no similar log-in credentials are used at the same time;
ensure that compensating controls are in place to address the risk involved in all cash collection processes;
enhance the monitoring and supervision of personnel, taking into consideration the risks involved in cash management;
ensure that all collecting officers, regardless of the classification of employment, are bonded as required in BTr TC No. 02-2019; and
increase the security controls with CCTVs and security cameras in areas handling critical processes in collection.
We further recommended that the management expedite the investigation on the alleged fraudulent activity, and filing appropriate charges against personnel involved and enforce collection of the stolen amount, if warranted. We also recommended that the reinstated personnel be transferred to another office, until she is absolved from the charges filed against her.

We recommended and management agreed to:
revisit their procedure on the budget formulation for the PPMP of end-users. BAC-TWG should extend help to the end-users to consider all factors in setting an indicative budget for procurement;
meticulously review of PPMP, including scrutiny of its supporting documents of the indicative budget, before its approval;
revise the existing PPMP to ensure that the quality of the procured goods is reflective of their corresponding fair market value; and
discontinue the practice of tailor-fitting the purchase request forms, as required in Section 18 of the revised RA 9184.

We recommended the City Mayor to direct the CSWMB and CENRO to do the following courses of actions:

Review the City Solid Waste Management Plan vis-à-vis with the deficiencies noted and try to point out the reasons why the Plan was not effectively implemented. Adopt other measures or even revise the existing one to suit it with the existing condition;

Closely involve the barangay officials in the strict implementation of the existing environmental laws and intensify the information campaign on the “no segregation, no collection policy”;

Monitor the establishment of MRF in the barangay level. Create a business opportunity that will encourage the barangay and its constituents to support the project;

Adopt specific revenue-generating measures to promote the viability of its Solid Waste Management Plan; and

Address the other deficiencies noted to comply with the mandates provided in R.A 9003 and CSWMP.

Coordinate and involve the barangays officials whenever a property could not be located since they also benefit from the collection of the corresponding property tax;

Strategize a scheme in scheduling regular or periodic follow-up collection; and

For unresponsive taxpayers, apply stringent approach using legal remedies in the collection of delinquent taxes.

Review the City’s Solid Waste Management Plan for purposes of ensuring its sustainability, viability, effectiveness and relevance in relation to local and international developments in the field of solid waste management;

Establish a system about the City’s waste diversion target. The said system should be congruent to the City’s Solid Waste Management Plan approved by the Commission. The system must include a performance indicator to monitor the status of diversion waste implementation particularly its goal on the year 2023 that Digos City  should have a 100% diversion  of waste generated from its disposal facilities;

Monitor the implementation of the City Solid Waste Management Plan through its various political subdivisions and in cooperation with the private sector and the NGOs;

Adopt measures to promote and ensure the viability and effective implementation of solid waste management programs in its component barangays especially the proper segregation of waste and establishment of Material Recovery Facility; and

Intensify the information, education and communication and advocacy campaign programs of the City especially on the segregation, reduction, re-use and recycling of wastes to encourage constituents’ awareness on Solid Waste Management Law (Ordinance).

The management will establish a system on how to collect efficiently the loan granted to various NGOs/POs. Define the roles and duties of the CLAP  and the CCDO from the granting and the  collection of the loans, so that we can establish the responsibility and the accountability;

Both the parties should revisit the MOA and evaluate what are the terms in the said agreement needed to be complied with and what are the possible solutions on the problems encountered by both parties; and

Maintain complete records of all borrowers including all the necessary information that could help the management in evaluating whether the accounts are considered impaired or not.

Reclassify the procured spare parts as inventory since these items were not yet delivered to the beneficiaries;

Provide the City’s counterpart of P425,000.00. Thereafter, conduct the required training of the beneficiaries’ officers and staff to equip them with the technical knowhow in running the store;

Record the release as Due from NGOs/POs to establish accountability upon implementation of the project and release of the motorcycle spare parts to the beneficiaries. Credit the account only upon submission of the liquidation report;

Conduct monitoring and inspection on a regular basis as assurance that the project will be successful to help augment the income of the members of the association; and

Ensure the timely preparation and submission of the Quarterly and Terminal Reports.

The City Assessor’s Office should conduct actual field inspection/ validation of the properties included in their assessment to determine the accuracy of their records and to effect appropriate adjustment based on the result of their field work;

Instruct the City Treasurer to coordinate with the Barangay Officials to locate the present address of the delinquent taxpayers and send demand letters to remind them of their unpaid taxes. Posting of the notices of delinquency in publicly accessible and conspicuous places and/or publication of the same in a local newspaper of general circulation is also recommended; and

Fast track the enhancement of the Real Property Tax System that will link the CTO and CAO records to expedite the generation of the necessary reports required for the efficient collection of taxes.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Direct the HRMO to review and update the Organization Structure and Staffing Patern, and also create a written policy and manual on hiring Job Order Personnel and Technical Advisers, in order to properly determine the additional manpower to be augmented;
Direct the personnel in-charge of hiring job orders to execute a contract of service or memorandum of agreement specifying therein the expected work of service to be accomplished by the concerned job order which shall be the basis for the preparation of monthly reports, evaluation and assessment of their individual performance;
Direct the personnel in-charge in the management of Job Order Personnel to require each and every JOs to properly accomplish their DTRs without erasures and alterations, and to strategize a system that would facilitate faster preparation of documents, without sacrificing proper assessment and transparency;
Direct the personnel in-charge of the management of Technical Advisers to ensure that contract of service indicates the necessary dates for proper management of the contract more effectively by making record keeping more accurate.;
Direct the personnel in-charge of the assessment of accomplishment of Technical Advisers to require the latter to properly indicate in their accomplishment reports the actual work done, indicating the names, titles, quantities, and other necessary information vital for assessment of accomplishments. Also, require the personnel in-charge to document its assessment and verification of the accomplishments of the technical advisers; and
Require the personnel in-charge to direct the technical advisers to submit their Personal Data Sheet (PDS) and other necessary documents that indicates their field of expertise.

We recommended the Management to:

1.	Stop the utilization of 20% DF for expenses not in adherence with the set guidelines of DBM-DILG JMC No. 2017-01 and see to it that charges against the 20% DF shall partake only expenditures which are investment or capital in nature to avoid disallowances in audit;

2.	Ensure the maximum utilization of the 20% DF through the implementation of all identified priority projects embodied in the AIP which shall contribute to the attainment of desirable socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes;

3.	Enjoin the LDC to amend or update the AIP in case of changes of PPAs and submit the same to SP for the issuance of resolution to authorize the augmentation or realignment of appropriation; and

4.	Submit justifications as to why the expenditures noted were charged against the 20% DF.

We recommended the City Mayor to require the person in charge of the project to:

Prepare the status of accomplishment of the project as at December 31, 2018 and determine the status of the livestock, and require beneficiaries to give written justification had there been any loss, death and other unfavorable issues unreported to the Office of the City Agriculturist;

Prepare written reports in every succeeding site inspection and monitoring to be conducted, and prepare accomplishment reports to be submitted to the source agency. This also applies to other projects of the Office of the City Agriculturist that requires submission of monthly physical and financial accomplishment reports;

Address the defects noted in the “Livestock Dispersal Contract” so that compliance thereof will be assured; and

For succeeding similar projects, commence the implementation of the projects upon receipt of the funding from various agencies, so that difficulties/challenges in the implementation of the projects can be identified ahead of the time to permit necessary adjustments and modifications to successfully complete the projects. 

We also recommended to the management, through the Local Chief Executive, to make written representation to the Regional Executive Director of DA - RFO XI and request for the approval to use the remainder of the fund to continue the project and reach out more beneficiaries should the management decides to use the remaining fund instead of remitting it back to DA – RFO XI.

We recommended the following:

For project undertaken by the administration, direct the City Engineer and project in-charges to address the deficiencies cited above before major defects occur whereby the City may need significant budget to correct/repair the project;

For projects undertaken by contract, require all the concerned contractors to immediately rectify the defects;

Direct the City Engineering Office to strategize a scheme in scheduling their personnel for a regular monitoring and supervision to ensure the quality of construction works of the contractors and workers;

Address the need for the installation of drywall partition of health center in Brgy. Aplaya; and

Conduct proper planning and site inspection before shortlisting the project for best outcomes.

The Project-in-Charge submits the distribution list for the 11,250 pieces of rubber seedlings for validation;
 Furnish the Audit Team with a monthly physical and financial report submitted to the DA-RFO XI also for validation;

Consider the weather condition in implementing projects that are dependent on the weather for survival or the selection of beneficiaries who can commit to devote time and effort to monitor the project with 100% or at least 90% of survival rate to avert wastage of government funds;

Require the Project-in-Charge of the Fishery Project to submit justification why four beneficiaries were given complete set of fishing equipment and gears when they have not attended the project orientation and pre-implementation meeting as required in the MOA;
The LCE require the Project-in-Charge to prioritize the completion of the projects funded from the BUB funds. Address the issues and concerns that delay/hinder the early completion of the project;
Cause the refund/return of excess funds to the Department of Agriculture and to the General Fund (excess counterpart) of completed projects; and
Require the City Accountant to prepare appropriate adjusting entries on the erroneous charging of expenses.

The LCE require the personnel responsible in the implementation of these projects to fast track the preparation of the programs-of-work utilizing the funds provided for the purpose. If the funds are no longer needed, remit to the Bureau of the Treasury in order to make available funds for other LGUs;

The City should maximize the use of the livelihood fund, and that any collection from the NGOs/POs should be programmed for release to other qualified NGOs/POs taking into account the guidelines of COA Circular No. 2007-01; and

The City should remit to the Bureau of the Treasury the excess amount from the completed road construction projects totaling P51,240.59.

Require the Local Development Council to come up with a detailed Annual Investment Plan (AIP) through consultation and deliberation with the concerned City and Barangay officials;

Incorporate in the AIP the complete description of the project, exact location, intended beneficiaries and estimated cost of each project; and

Make sure that only those projects in the approved AIP will be implemented. Otherwise, the Sanggunian should pass a resolution for the reversion, if warranted.

Conduct surveys on different schools covered by the City to ensure that all concerns are considered in the prioritization of projects for possible inclusion in the preparation of the SEF budget;

Review the reasonableness and necessity of the amount provided for every expense item.  Consider past transactions to come up with realistic budget, such that a bigger portion of the budget may be allocated for the construction, repair and rehabilitation of school buildings and other facilities;

Consider the balances from the continuing allotments consisting of excess funds     from implemented projects to be used as source of fund for the supplemental budget; and

Implement projects lined up for the year funded from both the current year and continuing appropriations especially on the construction, repair and rehabilitation of school buildings and other facilities.

The CCDO and CLAP shall share in the number of beneficiaries to be monitored to make it more manageable;

The LCE require the CCDO and CLAP to conduct ocular inspection of the NGOs/POs’ business site and remind them of their responsibility to pay or liquidate the funds granted to them as agreed upon in the MOA; and

Require also the submission of the monthly monitoring report as basis in what course of action to take to enforce collection and/or liquidation.

Proper coordination must be established between the Bids and Awards Committee, City Engineering, Budget and the City Planning Development Offices regarding the preparation of the report on the PPAs implemented and to be implemented by the City Government;

See to it that reported PPAs are reconciled against the records maintained by the BAC, City Engineering, City Budget and City Planning Development Offices before submission to COA for audit/validation; and

Require the concerned official/City Engineering Office to submit at the beginning of the year, the list of all on-going projects and those that are to be implemented during the year in accordance with the provision of 2.1 of COA Circular No. 2013-004 dated January 30, 2013 and provide our Office of any corrections/revisions or changes to the projects to be implemented for our validation/monitoring.

Provide the City’s counterpart for the projects to be implemented by the City Social Welfare and Development Office. Devise a system whereby procurement can be accomplished or completed at reasonable period;

The City Health Office should calendar the activities to be undertaken in line with the purpose for which the funds were received;

Reclassify the charging for the purchase of vegetable seeds, fertilizers and capability building expenses of P126,460.00 which was erroneously charged to the DA-RFO XI funds instead of LGU counterpart as stipulated in the MOA; and

Cause the return/refund to the source agency if funds are no longer needed to finance the projects of other LGUs.

